HTML Form Elements

Following are the different HTML Form Elements :-

â€¢ <form> - It defines an HTML form for user input. 

The HTML  <form> element can contain one or more of the following form elements. They are :-

1) The <input> Element -  The most used form element is the <input> element. It defines an input control. It can be displayed in several ways, depending on the "type" attribute.
  
       for ex- <label for="fname">First name:</label>
                  <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname">

2) The <label> Element - It defines a label for an <input> element. The <label> element is useful for screen-reader users, because the screen-reader will read out loud the label when the user focus on the input element.

                          The for attribute of the <label> tag should be equal to the id attribute of the <input> element to bind them together.

3) The <select> Element - It defines a drop-down list. 
                         for ex - <label for="cars">Choose a car:</label>
                                     <select id="cars" name="cars">
                                     <option value="volvo">Volvo</option>
                                     <option value="saab">Saab</option>
                                     <option value="fiat">Fiat</option>
                                     <option value="audi">Audi</option>
                              </select>

    In the above example, The <option> elements defines an option that can be selected.

4) The <textarea> Element - It defines a multi-line input control (a text area).  
                         for ex - <textarea name="message" rows="10" cols="30">
                                      The cat was playing in the garden.
                                    </textarea>

           In the above example, 
                   The "rows" attribute pecifies the visible number of lines in a text area.
                   The "cols" attribute specifies the visible width of a text area.

5) The <button> Element - It defines a clickable button. 
                      for ex - <button type="button" onclick="alert('Hello World!')">Click Me!                                   </button> 
           Always specify the "type" attribute for the button element.

6) The <fieldset> Element - It is used to group related data in a form. It represents a set of controls in a form, optionally grouped under the same name. 

                           For ex - <form action="/action_page.php">
                                  <fieldset>
                                          <label for="fname">First name:</label><br>
                                          <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname" value="John"><br>
                                          <label for="lname">Last name:</label><br>
                                          <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname" value="Doe"><br><br>
                                          <input type="submit" value="Submit">
                                  </fieldset>
                          </form>

7) The <legend> Element - It defines a caption for the <fieldset> element.

                            For ex - <form action="/action_page.php">
                                          <fieldset>
                                              <legend>Personalia:</legend>
                                              <label for="fname">First name:</label><br>
                                              <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname" value="John"><br>
                                              <label for="lname">Last name:</label><br>
                                              <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname" value="Doe"><br><br>
                                              <input type="submit" value="Submit">
                                          </fieldset>
                                      </form>

8) The <datalist> Element - It specifies a list of pre-defined options for an <input> element.
      The list attribute of the <input> element, must refer to the id attribute of the <datalist> element.
      
            For ex - <form action="/action_page.php">
                          <input list="browsers">
                          <datalist id="browsers">
                          <option value="Internet Explorer">
                          <option value="Firefox">
                          <option value="Chrome">
                          <option value="Opera">
                          <option value="Safari">
                      </datalist>
                   </form>

9) The <output> Element - It represents the result of a calculation (like one performed by a script).

            For ex -  <form action="/action_page.php"
                     oninput="x.value=parseInt(a.value)+parseInt(b.value)">
                             0
                     <input type="range"  id="a" name="a" value="50">
                       100 +
                      <input type="number" id="b" name="b" value="50">
                      =
                      <output name="x" for="a b"></output>
                     <br><br>
                     <input type="submit">
</form>
